@node Introduction "Introduction"

                                 @{b}Introduction@{ub}

    Have you fonts (bitmap, intellifont) that you want to look it without
using big program? Use ShowFont!

    Do you want show in selected place of your public screen any requester
that will shuts up after 5 (maybe 6? 10?) seconds or after closing them?
ShowFont is waiting...

    In polish instruction there is history of idea of ShowFont. If you can
understand polish texts you can read it - click on "Do czego ten program
sÓu˚y?" button in polish version of this guide. Sorry that there is not
this story... maybe in future I will translate it.

@endnode

@node Instructions "Instructions"

                                 @{b}Instructions@{ub}

    If you will type "ShowFont ?" in CLI/Shell after copying it to your C:
directory, you should see arguments list:

  FONTNAME/A,FONTSIZE/A/N,DELAY=DL/N,TEXT=TXT/K,SAVE=SV/K,XWIN=XW/N/K,
  YWIN=YW/N/K,PUBSCREEN=PUBSCR/K,FOREGROUND=FG/N/K,BACKGROUND=BG/N/K:

where:


    FONTNAME/A - font name. You can include here directory where it is
                 (default system use "FONTS:"). Eg.  'xhelvetica.font',
                 '.font' extension is obsolete
                 (required argument!)

    FONTSIZE/A/N - font size, eg. '13' (required argument!)

    DELAY=DL/N - time (in 1/50 [PAL] or 1/60 [NTSC] sec.) that after window
                 is automatically closed, eg. '200' or 'DELAY=300'

    TEXT=TXT/K - text to show in window in exchange of standard text (one
                 line), eg. 'TXT=" This is text! "'

    SAVE=SV/K - name of iff file where windows contents should be saved

    XWIN=XW/N/K - position x of left-up point of window on screen, eg.
                  'XWIN=10'

    YWIN=YW/N/K - position y of left-up point of window on screen, eg.
                  'YWIN=40'
    
    PUBSCREEN=PUBSCR/K - name of public screen on which window should be
                 open (default: default public screen, usually Workbench),
                 eg. 'FM'

    FOREGROUND=FG/N/K - foreground color number

    BACKGROUND=BG/N/K - background color number

Examples of using:

    ShowFont topaz.font 11

    ShowFont xhelvetica 15 100 XWIN=100 TEXT=" Ave, Thufor! "
            you can insert it in startup sequence, for egzample

    ShowFont ram:divine.font 121

    ShowFont CGTimes 45 PUBSCREEN=FM

    ShowFont Sitek 8 SV="DH1:Gfx/ScreenShots/Fonts/sitek_8.iff" FG=2 BG=0 DL=10

@endnode

@node Requirements "System requirements"

                                 @{b}Requirements@{ub}

    - Amiga with OS3.0+
    - diskfont.library V39+ (OS3.0+)
    - some free memory (it depends on font size and number of colors of
      screen where the window is opened)

                                @{b}Additional@{ub}

    - bullet.library V39+ (OS3.0+) when you want to see vector fonts
      (Intellifont)

                              @{b}Technical info@{ub}

    - program is CLI/Shell command
    - when runned under Workbench using icon it doesn't hang up, as it is
      with several cammands
    - it's short (in size)

    C source contents 5 files, summary long about 1000 lines of code
(excluding system includes).

    It was tested on Amiga 1200/030/28 MHz/882/28 MHz/2 MB Chip/8 MB
Fast/HD/SVGA using Enforcer and MungWall.

@endnode

@node Errors "Error messages"

                                @{b}Error Messages@{ub}

    Font size could be max. 255! - you entered too big size

    Couldn't open 'nazwafontu'.  - you typed wrong font name, path to font,
                                   file is not a font...

    Program also returns return code in environment variable RC. It is
usable in scripts, eg.

    Return codes:

     5 - in this version it isn't returned...
    10 - font can't be opened, font size is too big
    20 - failed to open library (OS is too old - required 3.0+, there isn't
         needed library on disk...), not enough memory, etc.


@endnode

@node Installation "Installation"

                                 @{b}Installation@{ub}

    Simply copy ShowFont file to your C: directory.

@endnode

